ey, Renfrewshire, Skotland, United Kingdom","Cochrane, Renfrew, Scotland":"Renfrewshire, Skotland"},"nl":{"about 1315–1400":"circa 1315–1400","1315–1400":"1315–1400","1344–Male":"1344–Overleden","1365–Male":"1365–Overleden","1315":"1315","1400":"1400","1344":"1344","1365":"1365","about 1315":"circa 1315","Cochrane, Renfrew, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Renfrew, Renfrewshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Paisley, Renfrewshire, Schotland","Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Paisley, Renfrewshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Cochrane, Renfrew, Scotland":"Renfrewshire, Schotland"},"en":{"about 1315–1400":"about 1315–1400","1315–1400":"1315–1400","1344–Male":"1344–Deceased","1365–Male":"1365–Deceased","1315":"1315","1400":"1400","1344":"1344","1365":"1365","about 1315":"about 1315","Cochrane, Renfrew, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Renfrew, Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland","Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Cochrane, Renfrew, Scotland":"Renfrewshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bird","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: nickname for a young or a small and slender person, from Middle English <i>brid</i>, <i>bird</i>, <i>burd</i> (Old English <i>bird</i>, <i>brid</i>, perhaps also <i>byrd</i>) ‘bird, young bird’, also ‘young man, young woman, child’.","Irish: Anglicized form of a number of Irish names erroneously thought to contain the element <i>éan</i> ‘bird’, in particular <i>Ó hÉinigh</i> (see   Heagney  ), <i>Ó hÉanna</i> (see   Heaney  ), <i>Ó hÉanacháin</i> (see   Heneghan  ), and <i>Mac an Déaghanaigh</i> (see   McEneaney  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of various European surnames meaning ‘bird’, as for example German and Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Vogel  , French   Loiseau  , Czech <b>Ptáček</b> (see   Ptacek  ) and <b>Pták</b>, Polish   Ptak  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Kingbird","meanings":["Native American (Chippewa; also <b>King Bird</b>): translation into English of the Chippewa personal name <i>Ogimaa-bines(i)</i>, meaning literally ‘the bird that is king’ and referring to the mythological bird-like creature thunderbird. See also   Bird   4.","History: The progenitor of the large family of the Kingbirds from the Red Lake, MN, was Ogimaa-bines, a musical gifted Chippewa spiritual leader."]},{"name":"Byrd","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Bird  ."]},{"name":"Heaney","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Aidan, Malachy, Nuala, Ronan.","Irish:","Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hÉanna</b> and <b>Ó hÉinne</b>, ‘descendant of <i>Éanna</i>’, a very common personal name of uncertain meaning. It was borne by various early Christian saints, most notably Saint Éanna of Aran. The name has been erroneously understood as containing the element <i>éan</i> ‘bird’ and as a result the surname was sometimes Anglicized as   Bird  ."]},{"name":"Blackbird","meanings":["Native American (also <b>Black Bird</b>): translation into English of a personal name such as Lakota Sioux <i>Ziŋtkala Sapa</i>, which is composed of <i>ziŋtkala</i> ‘bird’ and <i>sapa</i> ‘black’. See also   Bird   4.","English (Durham): nickname for someone with a dark beard, from Middle English <i>blak</i> ‘black’ + <i>berd</i> ‘beard’ (Old English <i>blæc</i> + <i>beard</i>)."]},{"name":"Burd","meanings":["English: variant of   Bird  .","Jewish (from Poland and Ukraine): nickname for a man with a notable beard, from a southern Yiddish pronunciation of Yiddish <i>bord</i> ‘beard’."]},{"name":"Burt","meanings":["English (southern): variant of   Bird  ,   Bright  , or   Burd  .","German: Middle High German <i>burt</i> ‘that which is due or proper’, therefore a nickname for someone who has fulfilled his obligations properly.","Jewish (from Poland and Ukraine): variant of   Burd  ."]},{"name":"Hummingbird","meanings":["Native American (Cherokee): translation into English of a personal name based on the Cherokee name <i>walela</i> for a hummingbird. See also   Bird   4."]},{"name":"Heagney","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hÉignigh</b>, ‘descendant of <i>Éigneach</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘forceful’. The spelling of the Irish name was often simplified to <b>Ó hÉinigh</b> and then Anglicized as   Heaney   or ‘translated’ as   Bird  , the latter because of a perceived similarity to <i>éan</i> ‘bird’."]}]},{"name":"Mary","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Maria</i> via Old Welsh <i>Meir</i>.  See  <b>Mary</b> ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Francis","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of Italian Francesco , originally a vocabulary word meaning ‘French’ or ‘Frenchman’ (Late Latin <i>Franciscus</i>;  compare  Frank  ). This was a nickname given to  St Francis  of Assisi (  1181–1226 ) because of his wealthy father's business connections with France. His baptismal name was  Giovanni . He had a pleasant, ordinary life as a child and young man, but after two serious illnesses, a period of military service, and a year as a prisoner of war in Perugia, he turned from the world and devoted himself to caring for the poor and sick. He was joined by groups of disciples, calling themselves ‘minor friars’ (<i>friari minores</i>). The main features of the Franciscan rule are humility, poverty, and love for all living creatures. The given name occurs occasionally in England as early as  1300 , and more frequently from the early 16th century, when there was a surge of admiration for, and imitation of, Italian Renaissance culture."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mary Francis de Bird was born about 1315, in Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. She had at least 2 sons with Goseline de Cochrane. She died in 1400, in her hometown, at the age of 86."},"et":{"about 1315–1400":"umbes 1315–1400","1315–1400":"1315–1400","1344–Male":"1344–Surnud","1365–Male":"1365–Surnud","1315":"1315","1400":"1400","1344":"1344","1365":"1365","about 1315":"umbes 1315","Cochrane, Renfrew, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Renfrew, Renfrewshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland","Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Paisley, Renfrewshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Cochrane, Renfrew, Scotland":"Renfrewshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"about 1315–1400":"noin 1315–1400","1315–1400":"1315–1400","1344–Male":"1344–Kuollut","1365–Male":"1365–Kuollut","1315":"1315","1400":"1400","1344":"1344","1365":"1365","about 1315":"noin 1315","Cochrane, Renfrew, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Renfrew, Renfrewshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland","Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Paisley, Renfrewshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Cochrane, Renfrew, Scotland":"Renfrewshire, Scotland"},"fr":{"about 1315–1400":"environ 1315–1400","1315–1400":"1315–1400","1344–Male":"1344–Décédé","1365–Male":"13